<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=African_American_Vernacular_English&action=edit&section=16.php.html" title="Edit section: External links and further reading">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="External_links_and_further_reading">External links and further reading</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><span class="citation" id="CITEREFDelpitDowdy2002">Delpit, Lisa; Dowdy, Joanne Kilgour (2002), <i>The Skin that We Speak: Thoughts on Language and Culture in the Classroom.</i>, New York: New Press, <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/1-56584-544-7" title="Special:BookSources/1-56584-544-7">1-56584-544-7</a></span></li>
<li><span class="citation web">McDorman, Richard E. (2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.richardmcdorman.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Understanding-African-American-English_Richard-E-McDorman.pdf">"Understanding African-American English: A Course in Language Comprehension and Cross-Cultural Understanding for Advanced English Language Learners in the United States"</a><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.richardmcdorman.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Understanding-African-American-English_Richard-E-McDorman.pdf">http://www.richardmcdorman.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/Understanding-African-American-English_Richard-E-McDorman.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 10-08-2012</span>.</span></li>
<li><span class="citation" id="CITEREFNunberg1997"><a href="Geoffrey_Nunberg" title="Geoffrey Nunberg">Nunberg, Geoffrey</a> (1997), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www-personal.umich.edu/~jlawler/wow/nunberg.html">"Double Standards"</a>, <i>Natural Language and Linguistic Theory</i> <b>15</b> (3): 667–675, <a href="Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1023/A:1005815614064">10.1023/A:1005815614064</a><span class="printonly">, <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www-personal.umich.edu/~jlawler/wow/nunberg.html">http://www-personal.umich.edu/~jlawler/wow/nunberg.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved 03-04-2010</span></span></li>
<li><span class="citation web">Oubré, Alondra (1997). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.aawc.com/ebonicsarticle.html">"Black English Vernacular (Ebonics) and Educability: A Cross-Cultural Perspective on Language, Cognition, and Schooling"</a>. <i>African American Web Connection</i><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.aawc.com/ebonicsarticle.html">http://www.aawc.com/ebonicsarticle.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 03-04-2010</span>.</span></li>
<li><span class="citation web">Patrick, Peter L. (2007). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://privatewww.essex.ac.uk/~patrickp/aavesem/Biblio.html">"A bibliography of works on African American English"</a>. University of Essex.<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://privatewww.essex.ac.uk/~patrickp/aavesem/Biblio.html">http://privatewww.essex.ac.uk/~patrickp/aavesem/Biblio.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 03-04-2010</span>.</span></li>
<li><span class="citation web">Pollock, K.; Bailey, G.; Berni; Fletcher; Hinton, L.N.; Johnson; Roberts; Weaver (1998). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.rehabmed.ualberta.ca/spa/phonology/features.htm">"Phonological Features of African American Vernacular English (AAVE)"</a>. <i>Child Phonology Laboratory</i>. University of Alberta<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.rehabmed.ualberta.ca/spa/phonology/features.htm">http://www.rehabmed.ualberta.ca/spa/phonology/features.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 03-04-2010</span>.</span></li>
<li><span class="citation web"><a href="John_Rickford" title="John Rickford" class="mw-redirect">Rickford, John R.</a> (December 1996). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.stanford.edu/~rickford/ebonics/EbonicsExamples.html">Ebonics "Ebonics Notes and Discussion"</a><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.stanford.edu/~rickford/ebonics/EbonicsExamples.html">http://www.stanford.edu/~rickford/ebonics/EbonicsExamples.html</a> Ebonics</span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 03-04-2010</span>.</span></li>
<li><span class="citation" id="CITEREFRickfordRickford1995"><a href="John_Rickford" title="John Rickford" class="mw-redirect">Rickford, John R.</a>; Rickford, Angela E. (1995), <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.edu-cyberpg.com/Linguistics/DIALECT_READERS_REVISITED.html">"Dialect readers revisited"</a>, <i>Linguistics and Education</i> <b>7</b> (2): 107–128, <a href="Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/0898-5898(95)90003-9">10.1016/0898-5898(95)90003-9</a><span class="printonly">, <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.edu-cyberpg.com/Linguistics/DIALECT_READERS_REVISITED.html">http://www.edu-cyberpg.com/Linguistics/DIALECT_READERS_REVISITED.html</a></span></span></li>
